 {"id":"bd-2alzw.5","title":"task(e2e): E2E test suite for Per-Frame Arena Allocation","description":"## E2E Integration Test: Per-Frame Arena Allocation (EV=24)

### Scope
Full integration test rendering all demo screens with bumpalo-based per-frame arena allocation on the render hot path. Validates that arena allocation is transparent (identical output) and logs allocation metrics per frame.

### Test Scenario
1. Initialize FrankenTUI with per-frame BumpArena enabled (bumpalo::Bump thread-local).
2. Render all demo screens for 10 frames each.
3. On each frame boundary, log arena usage before reset.
4. Compare every rendered frame hash against baseline (standard allocator).
5. Stress test: render complex nested widget trees (50+ depth) to exercise arena capacity.
6. Verify arena reset occurs exactly once per frame boundary.

### JSONL Structured Logging Specification
Each frame emits one JSONL line:
```json
{
  "event": "arena_frame",
  "ts_ns": u64,
  "frame_id": u64,
  "screen": "string",
  "arena_alloc_count": u32,
  "arena_bytes_used": u64,
  "arena_bytes_capacity": u64,
  "arena_reset": bool,
  "frame_hash": "hex_string",
  "baseline_match": bool,
  "alloc_time_ns": u64
}
```

### Success Criteria
- Zero visual diff: every frame_hash matches baseline (standard allocator).
- arena_reset == true exactly once per frame.
- No heap allocations on the hot render path (alloc_count from standard allocator == 0 during arena scope).
- No panics, no unsafe code (#![forbid(unsafe_code)], bumpalo is safe API only).
- JSONL log is schema-compliant and parseable.
- Memory usage does not grow across frames (arena resets properly).","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-02-13T22:24:06.614363380Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-02-13T22:26:56.538424062Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["e2e","logging","test"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-2alzw.5","depends_on_id":"bd-2alzw","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-02-24T21:26:00Z","created_by":"import","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-2alzw.5","depends_on_id":"bd-2alzw.3","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-02-24T21:26:00Z","created_by":"import","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"bd-2ao","title":"Implement Kitty keyboard protocol support (optional)","description":"# Implement Kitty Keyboard Protocol Support (Optional)

## Background
The plan mentions Kitty keyboard protocol in TerminalCapabilities detection and ADR-004. This is an optional enhancement that provides richer key event information.

## What Kitty Keyboard Protocol Provides
- Distinguish key press vs repeat vs release
- Modifier key events (Shift pressed, Shift released)
- Proper handling of key combinations
- Unicode codepoint of key
- Alternate key representations

## Why It's Optional (P3)
- Only supported by Kitty, WezTerm, Ghostty, foot
- Traditional CSI sequences cover most use cases
- Additional complexity for marginal benefit
- Feature-gated to avoid bloating core

## Technical Design

### Detection
```rust
impl TerminalCapabilities {
    pub fn detect() -> Self {
        // ...
        let kitty_keyboard = term.contains("kitty") ||
            std::env::var("KITTY_WINDOW_ID").is_ok() ||
            // Could also detect WezTerm, Ghostty
            false;
    }
}
```

### Protocol Activation
```rust
impl TerminalSession {
    pub fn enable_kitty_keyboard(&mut self) -> io::Result<()> {
        // CSI > flags u
        // flags: 0b1111 = disambiguate + report event types + report alternate keys + report all keys
        self.writer.write_all(b"\x1b[>15u")?;
        self.kitty_keyboard_active = true;
        Ok(())
    }

    pub fn disable_kitty_keyboard(&mut self) -> io::Result<()> {
        // CSI < u - pop keyboard mode
        self.writer.write_all(b"\x1b[<u")?;
        self.kitty_keyboard_active = false;
        Ok(())
    }
}
```

### Enhanced Event Type
```rust
pub struct KeyEvent {
    pub code: KeyCode,
    pub modifiers: Modifiers,
    pub kind: KeyEventKind,  // Press, Repeat, Release
    // Kitty-only extensions:
    pub base_codepoint: Option<char>,
    pub shifted_key: Option<char>,
}

pub enum KeyEventKind {
    Press,   // Key pressed
    Repeat,  // Key held down (auto-repeat)
    Release, // Key released
}
```

### Parser Extension
```rust
impl InputParser {
    fn parse_kitty_key(&mut self, seq: &[u8]) -> Option<Event> {
        // CSI unicode-codepoint ; modifiers ; event-type u
        // Parse the enhanced sequence
        // ...
    }
}
```

## Graceful Degradation
- If Kitty protocol not available, fall back to standard CSI
- KeyEventKind defaults to Press
- Optional fields are None for legacy input

## Tests Required
- [ ] Detection works for Kitty terminal
- [ ] Protocol activation/deactivation
- [ ] Parse enhanced key sequences
- [ ] Modifier key press/release events
- [ ] Graceful fallback when not supported
- [ ] RAII cleanup on exit

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Feature-gated behind `kitty-keyboard` feature
- [ ] Detection in TerminalCapabilities
- [ ] Activation/deactivation in TerminalSession
- [ ] Enhanced KeyEvent fields
- [ ] Parser handles Kitty sequences
- [ ] Falls back gracefully
- [ ] Documented in compatibility matrix

